  • This model shows promising results with no signs of overfitting.
Model option 1:¶
  • The training accuracy steadily increases with epochs, reaching around 91.4%, while the validation accuracy also improves and stabilizes around 89.2%.
  • This model shows promising results with no signs of overfitting. The curves for both accuracy and loss indicate stable learning without significant gaps between training and validation performance.
Model option 2:¶
  • The training accuracy improves to around 91.2%, while the validation accuracy stabilizes around 88.4%.
  • However, there is a slight increase in validation loss towards the end, indicating potential early signs of overfitting.
Model option 3:¶
  • The training accuracy improves to around 88.9%, and the validation accuracy stabilizes around 88.3%.
  • The increase in validation loss towards the end suggests that further training might worsen overfitting.

Conclusion:¶

  • Therefore, Model Option 1 is the preferred choice due to its stable and high performance on both training and validation sets without significant signs of overfitting.

Conclusion:¶

  • All three models (Original, Option 1, Option 2) appear to be converging on a good solution without significant overfitting. This is indicated by the training and validation accuracy curves being relatively close together.
  • Model Option 3 with dropout regularization might be slightly underfitting compared to the other models as the gap between training and validation accuracy is larger. You can try increasing the number of epochs or adjusting the dropout rate to see if it improves performance.
  • Model Option 1 (89.2%) currently has the highest validation accuracy.
  • The neural network model performed well in classifying fashion items, achieving 89.68% accuracy on the test set and 89.33% accuracy on the validation set. It also demonstrated strong precision (0.90), recall (0.90), and F1 score (0.90) on both sets.
